issue.title: Application Insights only tracking some types of calls
issue.body:
**Describe the bug**
We have a .net 6 application that reads/writes to cosmos collections via CosmosClient, and also has a ChangeFeedProcesser monitoring changes.

However, it seems that only the ChangeFeed related operations show up under dependencies in the Application Insights traces for the application.

When looking at the SDK source, it looks like telemetry is tracked via Open Telemetry. Should we not expect this to work with the standard Application Insights SDK?

**Expected behavior**
I would expect to see all the queries/updates through CosmosClient show as dependencies in Application Insights

**Environment summary**
We are using these nuget packages:
- Microsoft.ApplicationInsights.AspNetCore(2.21.0)
- Microsoft.Azure.Cosmos(3.34.0)

Running on Web Apps 4 containers in Azure (but the same thing is true for local dev box)

pull_request.title: [Internal] Query: Fixes optimalPageSize logic for OFFSET LIMIT in ORDER BY queries
pull_request.body:
## Description

This PR fixes the logic in CosmosQueryExecutionContextFactory where we determine optimal page size for ORDER BY queries that have an OFFSET/LIMIT clause.  Previously, the logic was only being applied to TOP and not OFFSET/LIMIT, resulting in suboptimal query execution (unnecessarily fetching more results than are likely to be needed by the query)

Consider an example query:
SELECT c.pk FROM c ORDER BY c.pk OFFSET 0 LIMIT 500

Without this change, we use a page size of 500 against each target range.  With this change, we will calculate an optimal page size based on the limit on the # of documents being requested (factoring in the number of target ranges) using the same formula that we already use for TOP queries:

```
                    // All partitions should initially fetch about 1/nth of the top value.
                    long pageSizeWithTop = (long)Math.Min(
                        Math.Ceiling(top / (double)targetRanges.Count) * CosmosQueryExecutionContextFactory.PageSizeFactorForTop,
                        top);

                    optimalPageSize = Math.Min(pageSizeWithTop, optimalPageSize);

```
## Type of change

- [] Bug fix (non-breaking change which fixes an issue)

pull_request.title: [Internal] Query: Fixes optimalPageSize logic for OFFSET LIMIT in ORDER BY queries
pull_request.body:
## Description

This PR fixes the logic in CosmosQueryExecutionContextFactory where we determine optimal page size for ORDER BY queries that have an OFFSET/LIMIT clause.  Previously, the logic was only being applied to TOP and not OFFSET/LIMIT, resulting in suboptimal query execution (unnecessarily fetching more results than are likely to be needed by the query)

Consider an example query:
SELECT c.pk FROM c ORDER BY c.pk OFFSET 0 LIMIT 500

Without this change, we use a page size of 500 against each target range.  With this change, we will calculate an optimal page size based on the limit on the # of documents being requested (factoring in the number of target ranges) using the same formula that we already use for TOP queries:

```
                    // All partitions should initially fetch about 1/nth of the top value.
                    long pageSizeWithTop = (long)Math.Min(
                        Math.Ceiling(top / (double)targetRanges.Count) * CosmosQueryExecutionContextFactory.PageSizeFactorForTop,
                        top);

                    optimalPageSize = Math.Min(pageSizeWithTop, optimalPageSize);

```
## Type of change

- [] Bug fix (non-breaking change which fixes an issue)
